  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Blue Petition for the King's Life
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Great Way is the root of yin and yang,
    From which all humanity springs forth.
    Heaven holds dominion over transformation's mystery,
    Yet crafts without imposing its will.

    Gazing upon this humble form,
    I have long relied on your true shelter.
    The mandate received knows no boundary—
    Only that the spirit might flourish bright,
    Inheriting the works of the Celestial Lord,
    While I pursue my desires tempered by reason.
    Yet my selection rests in Heaven's heart alone.

    Now as this moment of origins arrives,
    I await still more of your exalted grace.
    With reverence, I examine the rites of the Three Caverns,
    Offering pure and spotless sacrifice.
    I await the procession of immortals across the nine heavens,
    Hoping you will favor even this meager devotion.

    Let sincere hearts reach you—
    Grant swift aid and blessing.
    May ice melt into ease and leisure,
    Preserving the palace's peace and harmony,
    Bringing flourish to old and young alike,
    Extending the scroll of life without measure.
  footnotes:
    - This is a 'blue petition' (청사/靑詞), a Taoist prayer text used to petition celestial powers for blessing and longevity.
    - The 'Three Caverns' (三洞) refers to the three divisions of Taoist scripture and cosmology.
    - The 'nine heavens' (九霄) represents the celestial realm in Taoist and Chinese cosmological thought.
